LASSA FEVER, IMPORTED - GERMANY ex WEST AFRICA: ALERT
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
[see: Lassa fever, imported - Germany ex W.Africa
20000112221436]

*******************************
AIR PASSENGER ALERT
6 Jan 2000 Abidjan/Cote d'Ivoire - Lisbon Air Portugal flight no. TP
3149
7 Jan 2000 Lisbon - Frankfurt/M. Air Portugal flight no. TP 5576.
The Ministry for Social Affairs in Baden-Wuerttemberg issued the
following information on 12 January 2000 asking the media to
disseminate it nationally: "All passengers are urgently requested to
contact tomorrow (i.e. 13 Jan 2000) their local health departments.
Passengers with the following symptoms are asked to go to hospital
immediately: fever greater than 38.5 degrees C, headache, sore throat,
coughing and intestinal upset.
The following details are requested from passengers:
Name
Seat number
Contact address and telephone no.
*******************************
[1]
Date: Thu, 13 Jan 2000 10:33:01 +0100
From: leitritz@m3401.mpk.med.uni-muenchen.de
Via: Wolfgang Preiser <W.Preiser@em.uni-frankfurt.de>
Source: Press release of the Robert Koch-Institut, Berlin
(Translation by W. Preiser)

13.01.2000
Diagnosis of Lassa fever confirmed
A 23-year old female student who had been transferred from a hospital
in Schwaedbisch-Hall to the renowned Mission Hospital in Wuerzburg
on Tuesday, 11 Jan 2000, due to continuing high fever has been
confirmed as suffering from Lassa fever. The young woman who is
studying in Duesseldorf had returned to Germany at the beginning of
the year from a seven-week African holiday in Cote d'Ivoire (Ivory
Coast) and Ghana.
Lassa fever is caused by a virus which is transmitted to humans from a
small rat widely occurring in African dwellings -- mostly through food
contaminated with rodent excrement. Human-to-human transmission is
possible under bad hygienic conditions through direct contact with
blood, saliva, vomitus or urine from diseased individuals, particularly
during nursing. Most infected individuals start being infectious only
when they reach the acute febrile phase. The disease, a so-called viral
hemorrhagic fever, can lead to a severe bleeding disorder with shock
and circulatory collapse. In hospitalised patients mortality is about 15 %.
Often the disease may run a mild or asymptomatic course. There is
currently no vaccine.
After other diseases had been excluded and the suspicion of Lassa fever
corroborated, the necessary measures were co-ordinated in close
collaboration between the Medical Director of the Mission Hospital in
Wuerzburg, Professor Dr. Fleischer, the responsible outbreak
administrator of the Health Ministries of Bavaria and
Baden-Wuerttemberg, the Robert Koch-Institut (http://www.rki.de)
and the Bernhard Nocht-Institut in Hamburg
(http://www.bni.uni-hamburg.de) where the necessary laboratory
investigations are done. The Federal Health Ministry, the European
Union and the WHO were informed through the notification channels in
place for these cases.
The patient is being treated in an isolated part of the Hospital. She is
in a serious state. Isolation ensures that there is no risk for other
patients nor for the general population. Family members and friends
who had been in immediate contact, and the medical personnel who
looked after the patient in Schwaebisch Hall, are being interviewed by
the health authorities regarding details of their contacts and informed
about possible symptoms. Contact persons are being asked to take their
temperature twice daily, to be vigilant re possible symptoms and to
contact the Hospital in Schwaebisch Hall in case of symptoms. As it is a
rare but severe infectious disease the health authorities are doing
everything to prevent infection of others.
--
