[3]
Date: Thu, 13 Jan 2000 13:28:37 +0100
From: Wolfgang Preiser <W.Preiser@em.uni-frankfurt.de>
Source: Update information from the Robert Koch-Institute
13 January 1 p.m. local time (GMT+1)
(Translation W. Preiser)
Lassa fever import 7 January 2000
The 23-year old German student who was transferred from a hospital in
Schwaebisch Hall to the renowned Mission Hospital in Wuerzburg on
Monday, 10 January 2000, due to continuing high fever has been
confirmed with Lassa fever. The young woman who is studying in
Duesseldorf had returned to Germany from a seven-week holiday in
Cote d'Ivoire and Ghana on Friday, 7 January.
According to what is known so far she used the following flights back to
Frankfurt am Main:
06.01.2000 Abidjan/Cote d'Ivoire - Lisbon Air Portugal flight no.TP
3149
07.01.2000 Lisbon - Frankfurt/M. Air Portugal flight no. TP 5576.
An overnight stay in a hotel in Lisbon that was initially assumed now
seems very unlikely. Apparently she spent only a few hours in Lisbon in
or near the airport.
The Ministry for Social Affairs in Baden-Wuerttemberg issued the
following information on 12 January 2000 asking the media to
disseminate it nationally: "All passengers are urgently requested to
contact tomorrow (i.e. 13 Jan 2000) their local health departments.
Passengers with the following symptoms are asked to go to hospital
immediately: fever greater than 38.5 degrees C, headache, sore throat,
coughing and intestinal upset.
The following details are requested from passengers:
Name
Seat number
Contact address and telephone no.
The infection of the patient is due to the particular circumstances of
her travel (rural area, basic conditions). A particular risk for
travellers from Africa including West Africa, particularly Cote d'Ivoire
and Ghana, cannot be concluded from this case.
Taking into account the incubation period of Lassa fever of 6 to 21 days
(mostly 7 to 10 days) secondary cases are very unlikely to have onset of
disease before 13 Jan 2000.
--
Dr. Wolfgang Preiser, DTM&H, DipRCPath
Institut f. Medizinische Virologie
J. W. Goethe-Universitaet Frankfurt am Main
Paul Ehrlich-Str. 40, D-60596 Frankfurt am Main, Germany
Tel.: ++49 69 6301 5150; Fax: ++49 69 6301 6477
e-mail: w.preiser@em.uni-frankfurt.de or preiser@wildmail.com
[Although Lassa virus is a rodent-borne virus like the hantaviruses, it is
an arenavirus, a different group. Unlike the Andes hantavirus, Lassa
virus is not known to be transmitted through the air, only through
contact with body fluids. Unless an air passenger or crew member or
person in the airport came into contact with the blood, vomit, urine or
excrement of this unfortunate person, it is extremely unlikely that any
transmission occurred.
Remember the case of the sick Gabonese doctor who did not know he
had Ebola, & who travelled by commercial flight from Gabon to
Johannesburg, South Africa -- nobody on his flight contracted the
disease. Ebola is another hemorrhagic fever that is not transmitted
through the air. Ref: Ebola - South Africa (04) 961119121357. -
Mod.JW]
